```
Boolean `@tracked` properties are ideal when state is binary (open/closed, visible/hidden, on/off) — they work directly with `{{#if}}` and `{{unless}}` without any helper. String enums are better for async states with more than two meaningful values, because adding a third state (like `'retrying'`) to a boolean would require renaming and breaking changes. Use the simplest type that correctly models your state.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class SpreadsheetMentalModel extends Component {
  // Think of @tracked like a spreadsheet CELL — it holds a value
  // and any formula (getter) that references it auto-recalculates
  @tracked runs = 45;    // Cell A1
  @tracked balls = 30;   // Cell A2

  // Getter = spreadsheet FORMULA: =A1/A2*100
  // Recalculates automatically when A1 or A2 changes
  get strikeRate() {
    return ((this.runs / this.balls) * 100).toFixed(1);
  }

  // Template = spreadsheet DISPLAY CELL that references the formula
  // Re-displays automatically when the formula result changes

  <template>
    <p>Runs: {{this.runs}}</p>
    <p>Balls: {{this.balls}}</p>
    <p>SR (auto-computed): {{this.strikeRate}}</p>
  </template>
