"Derive, don't store" means: only put primitive, truly independent values in `@tracked`. Everything that can be computed from those values should be a getter. Storing derived data in `@tracked` creates a synchronization problem — you must remember to update `strikeRate` every time `runs` or `balls` changes. Getters are always correct by definition, cannot go stale, and re-compute automatically.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { cached } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class CachedVsPlain extends Component {
  @tracked players = [];

  // PLAIN GETTER: re-runs on every access by ANYONE
  // If three template expressions read this, it runs THREE times per render
  get topScorers() {
    console.log('topScorers recomputed');
    return [...this.players]
      .sort((a, b) => b.runs - a.runs)
      .slice(0, 5);
  }

  // @cached GETTER: re-runs ONCE per invalidation, result is cached
  // If three template expressions read this, it runs ONCE per render
  @cached
  get expensiveTopScorers() {
    console.log('expensiveTopScorers recomputed');
    return [...this.players]
      .sort((a, b) => b.runs - a.runs)
      .slice(0, 5);
  }

  <template>
    <ul>{{#each this.expensiveTopScorers as |p|}}<li>{{p.name}}</li>{{/each}}</ul>
  </template>
}
```
A plain getter runs on every access — if a template reads it in multiple expressions, it recomputes multiple times per render. `@cached` adds a per-instance memoization layer: the getter runs once and caches its result. Subsequent reads return the cached value until a tracked dependency changes. Only add `@cached` when profiling shows the getter is genuinely expensive (e.g., sorting/filtering large arrays). Overusing `@cached` adds memory overhead without benefit.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { cached } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class WhenToCache extends Component {
  @tracked matchHistory = [];

  // ADD @cached when:
  // 1. The getter is read multiple times per render
  // 2. The computation is expensive (sort, filter, heavy math)
  // 3. The result is a new object/array (reference stability matters for child components)
  @cached
  get processedMatchHistory() {
    return this.matchHistory
      .filter(m => m.result !== 'abandoned')
      .sort((a, b) => new Date(b.date) - new Date(a.date))
      .map(m => ({ ...m, formattedDate: new Date(m.date).toLocaleDateString() }));
  }

  // NO @cached needed — simple arithmetic, read once
  get totalWins() {
    return this.matchHistory.filter(m => m.result === 'win').length;
  }

  <template>
    <p>Wins: {{this.totalWins}}</p>
    {{#each this.processedMatchHistory as |match|}}
      <p>{{match.formattedDate}}: {{match.result}}</p>
    {{/each}}
  </template>
}
```
`@cached` stores the computed result on the component instance and returns it on subsequent reads until a tracked dependency changes. The three signals to add it: (1) the getter appears in multiple `{{#each}}` or conditional branches so it would run multiple times, (2) it involves sorting or filtering large arrays, (3) it returns a new array/object each time, which would cause unnecessary re-renders in child components that receive the result as an arg.

