React's `shouldComponentUpdate` exists because React re-renders entire component trees by default on state changes — developers need an escape hatch to prevent unnecessary re-renders. Glimmer's autotracking is inherently granular: only the specific template expressions that read a changed tracked value are invalidated. There is no "whole component re-render" concept — just individual expression invalidation. This makes Glimmer's rendering efficient by default, without any manual optimization hooks needed.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class ScoreboardComponent extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 0;

