```
`@action` exists to solve the `this` binding problem for methods passed as callbacks or event listeners. Lifecycle hooks — `constructor` and `willDestroy` — are always called directly by Glimmer on the component instance using explicit method invocation (`instance.willDestroy()`), so `this` is always correctly bound. Adding `@action` to them is harmless but redundant and misleading, implying they are user-facing event handlers when they are framework lifecycle callbacks.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class PlayerProfileComponent extends Component {
  @tracked selectedPlayer = null;

  get playerName() {
    // ✅ Use optional chaining — @tracked null is valid and reactive
    return this.selectedPlayer?.name ?? 'No player selected';
  }

  @action
  selectPlayer(player) {
