}
```
With a single `@tracked` object, every property mutation requires replacing the entire object reference. Any getter reading that object is invalidated even if it only cares about one field. Granular `@tracked` properties give Glimmer's autotracking system precise information: `runRate` tags `runs` and `overs` but not `isExpanded`, so toggling expansion never triggers `runRate` to recompute. This results in fewer unnecessary getter evaluations and more efficient renders, especially in components with many derived values.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class ProxyDemoComponent extends Component {
  // @tracked stores the Proxy reference, not the underlying object
  @tracked playerProxy = new Proxy(
    { name: 'Kohli', runs: 0 },
    {
      set(target, key, value) {
        target[key] = value;
        return true;
      }
    }
  );

  @action
  updateRuns() {
    // ❌ Proxy mutation does NOT invalidate @tracked tag — only reference change does
    // this.playerProxy.runs += 1;

    // ✅ Replace the Proxy reference — tag invalidated
    const target = { ...this.playerProxy };
    target.runs += 1;
    this.playerProxy = new Proxy(target, { set(t, k, v) { t[k] = v; return true; } });
  }
}
```
A plain `@tracked` property only tracks its own reference. Intercepting mutations via a Proxy does not notify Glimmer's autotracking system unless you explicitly consume and invalidate `@tracked` tags inside the Proxy trap. `TrackedObject` from `tracked-built-ins` is the correct solution — it uses a Proxy with Glimmer tracking built into its getter and setter traps. Rolling your own reactive Proxy is complex and error-prone; prefer `TrackedObject` for deep reactivity needs.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';

export default class MatchBadgeComponent extends Component {
  // No @tracked — getter only reads @args
  get matchLabel() {
    const { format, venue } = this.args;
    return `${format} at ${venue}`;
  }

  <template>
    <span>{{this.matchLabel}}</span>
  </template>
}
```
`this.args` in a Glimmer component is itself a tracked object — each argument property has an internal `@tracked`-like tag managed by the framework. When the parent re-renders and passes different values for `format` or `venue`, those argument tags are invalidated. Any getter (or template expression) that consumed those tags is marked as stale and re-runs on the next render. You do not need local `@tracked` properties for values derived purely from `@args` — getters reading args are already fully reactive without any additional decorator.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { cached } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class TournamentStandingsComponent extends Component {
  @tracked matches = [];

  // Plain getter: recomputes every time the template renders (even if matches unchanged)
  // get standings() { return this.#computeHeavy(); }

  // @cached getter: recomputes ONLY when `matches` tag is invalidated
  @cached
  get standings() {
    // Expensive: sorts and groups hundreds of match records
    return [...this.matches]
      .sort((a, b) => b.points - a.points)
      .map((m, i) => ({ ...m, rank: i + 1 }));
  }

  <template>
    {{#each this.standings as |team|}}
      <p>{{team.rank}}. {{team.name}}</p>
    {{/each}}
  </template>
}
```
Without `@cached`, a getter re-runs every time the render pass evaluates the template, even if none of its tracked dependencies changed. For lightweight getters, this is fine. For expensive computations — large array sorts, complex string formatting, or heavy calculations — `@cached` memoizes the result and only recomputes when a consumed `@tracked` tag is actually invalidated. The `@cached` decorator adds a small memory overhead (storing the cached value), so only apply it to genuinely expensive getters, not every getter in your component.

```gjs
// ParentComponent.gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';
import ScoreEditorComponent from './score-editor';

export default class ParentComponent extends Component {
  @tracked showEditor = true;

  @action toggle() { this.showEditor = !this.showEditor; }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" this.toggle}}>Toggle Editor</button>
    {{#if this.showEditor}}
      <ScoreEditorComponent /> {{! New instance each time — @tracked resets }}
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}

// If you need persistent state, lift it to parent @args or a service:
// <ScoreEditorComponent @score={{this.persistedScore}} @onUpdate={{this.saveScore}} />
```
Glimmer destroys a component instance when it leaves the DOM (e.g., when `{{#if}}` evaluates to false). All `@tracked` properties on that instance are garbage collected along with it. When `{{#if}}` becomes true again, a brand new instance is created with fresh initial values. This is the correct behavior — Glimmer does not cache destroyed component instances. To persist state across toggle cycles, lift the state out of the component: store it in the parent as `@tracked` and pass it down as `@args`, or use an Ember Service.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class ScoreConsistencyComponent extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 100;
  @tracked wickets = 3;

  get summary() {
    // Always reads both values from the same render pass — always consistent
    return `${this.runs}/${this.wickets}`;
  }

  @action
  recordDismissal(runsAdded) {
    this.runs += runsAdded;
    this.wickets += 1;
    // DOM still shows old values here — re-render is pending
  }

  <template><p>{{this.summary}}</p></template>
}
```
Glimmer's render cycle is synchronous and non-interruptible once it begins. All `@tracked` mutations within an `@action` accumulate dirty tags but do not trigger partial renders. Only after the action's call stack completes does Glimmer schedule a render. That render reads all tracked values in a single pass — `runs` and `wickets` are always read together within one consistent snapshot. There is no time between renders where `runs` has been updated but `wickets` has not, which would display `104/3` when the correct state is `104/4`. This atomic rendering guarantee eliminates an entire class of UI consistency bugs.
